Hi Philip

It was a contrived example, but is representative of actual events.  

You say you wouldn&#39;t expect such small species with such good fitnes,
but if it&#39;s a young specie, it may well be very small as a break away
(mutation) from a larger species.

This happens regardless of whether the compatability value remains
constant (and specie numbers vary) or the compatability score varies
whilst trying to keep the specie count constant. 

Ta

Matt

--- In neat@yahoogroups.com, Philip Tucker &lt;ptucker@g...&gt; wrote:
&gt; Was this a contrived example to illustrate your point, or did you
&gt; actually witness numbers this extreme in practice?  My guess is that
&gt; the population would never reach such an extreme dichotomy between
&gt; species because specie 3 never would have gotten that large unless its
&gt; fitness were dominating the others - which in this case it is not. 
&gt; Also, the species 1 and 2 likely would not be that small with such
&gt; good fitness.
&gt; 
&gt; - Philip
&gt; 
&gt; On 8/19/05, Matt Simmerson &lt;m.simmerson@b...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt; Hi
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; Whilst calculating the number of offspring for a valid (i.e. non
&gt; &gt; extinct and size &gt; 0) specie, the count returns 0.  This is
&gt; &gt; particularly prevalent in large species where the adjusted fitness
&gt; &gt; becomes quite small comapared with the rest of the other, and usually
&gt; &gt; much less populous, species.
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; This becomes even more marked if I boost young species fitness.
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; As far as I understand, the offspring is calculated as follows.
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; (av adjusted specie fitness) / (total of all species av adjusted
&gt; &gt; fitnesses) * Population size.
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; For example, imagine we have 3 species. Specie_1 has 3 members av raw
&gt; &gt; fitness 0.85, Specie_2 has 2 members av raw fitness 0.82 and Specie_3
&gt; &gt; has 145 members with av raw fitness 0f 0.9.
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; Specie_1(adj) = 0.85/3 = 0.28333
&gt; &gt; Specie_2(adj) = 0.82/2 = 0.41
&gt; &gt; Specie_3(adj) = 0.9/145 = 0.006
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; Specie_1 then generates 61 offspring
&gt; &gt; Specie_2 then generates 87 offspring
&gt; &gt; Specie_3 then generates 2 offspring
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; Not quite 0, but you get the idea.  So even though the largest specie
&gt; &gt; with has best average fitness, its population gets decimated.
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; I understand, that large species need to get penalised, but this seems
&gt; &gt; extreme and you are potentially losing a lot of good gemomes.
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; Ideas/correction/thoughts appreciated.
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; Ta
